Here are both approaches for Shell navigation in .NET MAUI:

**1. Register the route:**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate with a string parameter:**
```csharp
// ProductListPage.xaml.cs or ViewModel
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");
}
```

**3. Navigate with the full object:**
```csharp
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    var parameters = new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", parameters);
}
```

**4. Receive both on the ViewModel using `IQueryAttributable`:**
```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1: string parameter (arrives as string)
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
        {
            string productId = idObj.ToString();
            // Load product from service using productId
        }

        // Approach 2: full object (arrives as the original type)
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var productObj) && productObj is Product product)
        {
            // Use product directly — no need to fetch
            Name = product.Name;
            Price = product.Price;
        }
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| Method | Query string in URI | `Dictionary<string, object>` overload |
| Arrives as | `string` | Original CLR type |
| Survives serialization | Yes (deep-link safe) | No (in-process only) |

Use string IDs for deep-link/URI support; use objects when you already have the data in memory and don't need serialization.
